title: For Sale:  Armi Jager / Adler Jager AP-74 AP74 AP 74 .22 caliber M16A1 style
postcontent:
This is an Armi Jager / Adler Jager AP-74. It was purchased because I have an AP15 and figured the parts were interchangeable but they are not. It is sighted in for a bit farther than the average .22, but considering this particular example was formerly a training rifle for the Thai army, I can see why they might shoot to farther distances than the average shooter. Sights can easily be adjusted, has adjustable front and rear sight. This Italian made gun has the added bonus of field stripping just like an M16; remove the rear pin, pull the charging handle and the bolt will come with it. Also uses a buffer tube like a real M16. Has some blue paint on the front face of the gas block, probably to designate it wasn't a trainer and not a real one. Magazine is new by Triple-K and thus very tight, I suggest if you want it to function with 15 rounds instead of 10 like I've been loading that you load the magazine completely and l let it sit for half a year. These rifles are rarely seen in this good of a condition as commercial examples imported by Mitchell Arms almost always have broken dust covers that won't stay closed and most of the commercial rifles people are selling have a broken firing pin or extractor.

I'm asking $275; reasonable offers considered.

postcontent:
This is a FEG Hi-Power, made in Hungary. These are exact copies of the earlier Browning Hi-Power with completely interchangeable parts. Chambered in 9mm Parabellum, it is a former police gun, most likely from South Africa, it has a distributors renaming on it that's fairly worn off labeled as "LUGER M80" it is lightly pitted in some areas, when I first got it it was nickel plated with most the plating coming off. I sent it off to be cerakoted professionally (no part that is cerakoted will ever rust! No need to wipe down after handling if unfired.) they stripped and cleaned it thoroughly and refinished it black and white, including the magazine, the barrel (inside and out,) and every part of the gun on the inside and out except the firing pin and face of the bolt. Still has magazine safety, and is impressively accurate. I have been using it as my carry gun and not 100% sure I want to get rid of it as I sold it before and bought it back but I wouldn't mind having a Springfield XD or a Glock, maybe a S&W M59 and I don't have a lot of money right now.

If sale I'm asking: 275 (the friend I had sold it to had it in his shop at $450, so it's definitely worth at least 275!)

If trading: I'd be interested in, as said a Springfield XD or a Glock, S&W M59, will consider other offers for pistols and maybe some rifles. Not interested in shotguns unless you have a lever action.

This pistol could pretty well pass for NIB, but I have fired 9 rounds through it after I bought it.  It was then cleaned and put in my safe and it's been there ever since.  There is still the copper looking stuff from Glock inside of it.  I don't play games and say a firearm hasn't been fired and later claim "Oh, I just 'test fired' it".  If it's unfired, I state it's unfired.  If you can't tell, like this one, I admit that it has had 9 rounds down the tube then cleaned.  It comes with all the stuff that was shipped with a Gen3 Glock 27.  It basically looks like a new Glock 27.  I apologize in advance for those who haven't bought from me as I've been cleaning out some of collection; I price my firearms at what I feel is a very fair price and stick to that price. Compatibility:
The UltiMAK M8 mount fits only standard, GI spec barrels. In the current Springfield line-up, the compatible models are; M1A Standard, M1A Scout Squad, SOCOM 16, and SOCOM II. The "Loaded Standard" and all of their "Match" and "Tactical" models have heavier-than-standard barrels, which will not allow M8 mount installation. Chinese M1A clones have standard barrels and fit nicely with the M8 mount. title: For Sale/Trade:  Coyote Experiment
postcontent:
Hey guys,
I am a student at MSU Denver and am currently taking a class called Animal Behavior, or Ethology. My lab group has been tasked with designing an experiment concerning the behavior of animals, conducting said experiment, and then writing a scientific article about it. We chose to write about coyotes, specifically their behavior in regards to their proximity to urban development.
We are planning on setting up a game call in several places close to well populated areas (Aurora, Lakewood, Golden, etc) and then recording the response time of the coyotes to this call Then, we will conduct the same experiment in areas much more remote (Pawnee, Commanche, etc), and compare the data. What do you think, will the city coyotes be less timid and respond quicker out of curiosity, or will the wild coyotes with far less scavenging options than their city-dwelling kin come running to the sound of a free meal? We aim to find out!

So if you have any decent game cameras or remote-operated coyote calls that you won't be using between now and May, let me know, I would love to work out a rental arrangement and put some cash in your hand!

Thanks for taking the time to read this! 
-Mark
